[The referenced article can be accessed at http://www.pnas.org/content/early/2013/06/19/1304704110.

Before the discovery of the koala endogenous retrovirus (KoRV), mammalian endogenous retrovirus were thought not to produce infectious particles. KoRV retains its ability to form virus particles capable of 'de novo' infection transmission.

The study revealed that Los Angeles Zoo koalas with lymphomas/leukemias are infected with 2 subtypes of KoRB. "KoRV-A" (also present in koalas from San Diego zoo) and by a unique KoRV termed subtype "KoRV-B". KoRV-B is transmitted from dam to offspring through 'de novo' infection, rather than via genetic inheritance like KoRV-A. - Mod.PMB

